'''Caribbean Research and Management of Biodiversity Foundation''' (previously '''The Caribbean Marine Biological Institute'''; commonly referred to as '''CARMABI Foundation'''<ref name=researchstationcarmabi.orgContact>{{cite web|title=Contact|url=http://www.researchstationcarmabi.org/contact|publisher=CARMABI|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> or just '''CARMABI''') is a research organization in [[Curaçao]], former [[Netherlands Antilles]]. It is situated in [[Piscadera Bay]], {{convert|25|m}} from the [[Caribbean Sea]]. Its education and research programs include the [[ecological]] aspects of [[fisheries]] and [[coral reef]] sciences.<ref name=Ecology>{{Cite web|url=http://www.researchstationcarmabi.org/|title=CARMABI Research Institute|publisher=Research Station Carmabi Organization}}</ref>{{Sfn|Benson|Rehbock|2002|p=454}}{{Sfn|General Biological Supply House|1958|p=286}} 

==History==
In 1955, the head of Curaçao's petroleum industry proposed funding for a scientific institution at Piscadera Bay as it was noted to be a perfect location for research; subsequently, plans were drawn to establish the institution.{{Sfn|Caribbean Commission|1955|p=41}} Originally named the Caribbean Marine Biological Institute (CARMABI), the station was founded in 1955 at the bay's open end. Its work centered on research in the field of [[ecology]]—fisheries. As the bay front has extensive coral reefs, research in the field of coral reef science was initiated in 1969.  Consequent to increased participation in the activities of the institute, the CARMABI facility was enlarged, adding a new building with laboratory facilities on the shore line.  
Residential dormitories were also constructed to house 30 persons. By 1970, its facility contained wet and dry laboratories, an aquarium, as well as four work rooms.{{sfn|National Academy of Sciences|National Research Council|1970|p=161}} 

In association with National Parks Foundation of the  Netherlands Antilles (STINPA), CARMABI has conducted terrestrial and marine projects, CARMABI being associated with research while STINPA is associated with management.{{Sfn|Benson|Rehbock|2002|p=454}} In 1999, CARMABI and STINAPA became a single entity, renamed as the Caribbean Research and Management of Biodiversity Foundation, although continuing to be referred to as CARMABI.<ref name=researchstationcarmabi.orgHistory>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.researchstationcarmabi.org/the-station/history|publisher=CARMABI|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> CARMABI, the [[SECORE]] (SExual COral REproduction) Foundation and the [[Seaquarium Beach|Curaçao Sea-Aquarium]] jointly carried out a study in Curaçao, which involved developing the techniques needed to regenerate [[Depauperate ecosystem|depauperate]] ''Acropora palmate'' in the entire area of  the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/region10/pdf/diveteam/publications/2013_aaus_esdp_diving_for_science.pdf|title= Proceedings Joint International Scientific Diving Symposium American Academy Of Underwater Sciences And European Scientific Diving Panel|work= Restoration Of Critically Endangered Elkhorn Coral (''Acropora Palmata'') Using Sexually Produced Recruits |page=43|year=2013|publisher= American Academy of Underwater Sciences}}</ref> CARMABI Foundation, also associated with the management of the Christoffel Park and the Shete Boka Park, is "the largest field station in the [[Southern Caribbean]]".<ref name=Ecology/> Jacques S. Zaneveld of [[Old Dominion University]] was a former director.{{sfn|Zaneveld|1983|p=3}}

